claims:
1. A method comprising, by one or more computing devices associated with an online social network:
accessing, from a plurality of objects posted to the online social network, a set of training objects associated with a first object-classification;
identifying, by an initial object-classifier algorithm, from comments associated with the set of training objects, a first set of features, wherein the initial object-classifier algorithm is configured to classify objects posted to the online social network as associated with a first object-classification by comparing comments associated with each object to one or more features, wherein each feature has a corresponding text expression and a feature score indicating a correlation value between the associated feature and the first object-classification;
adding, to the object-classifier algorithm, the first set of features to generate a revised object-classifier algorithm;
accessing, from the plurality of objects, a set of test objects;
classifying, by the revised object-classifier algorithm, one or more of the test objects as associated with the first object-classification;
identifying, by the revised object-classifier algorithm, from comments associated with the one or more classified test objects, a second set of features having feature scores greater than a threshold feature score; and
adding, to the revised object-classifier algorithm, the second set of features to generate a final object-classifier algorithm.
2. The method of claim 1, further comprising:
accessing a social graph comprising a plurality of nodes and a plurality of edges connecting the nodes, wherein each edge between two nodes represents a single degree of separation between the two nodes, the plurality of nodes comprising:
a plurality of nodes corresponding to a plurality of users of the online social network, respectively, wherein a degree of separation between any two user nodes is a minimum number of edges required to traverse the social graph data from one user node to the other; and
a plurality of nodes corresponding to the plurality of objects posted to the online social network, respectively.
3. The method of claim 2, wherein each of the plurality of objects is a post by a first user of the online social network corresponding to a first user node and each comment associated with the object is a comment on the post by a second user of the online social network corresponding to a second user node.
4. The method of claim 3, wherein, for each of the plurality of objects, each second user node is within a single degree of separation from the first user node in the social graph.
5. The method of claim 3, wherein classifying the one or more test objects as associated with the first object-classification is based at least in part on, for each test object, an affinity coefficient between the first user and one or more of the second users.
6. The method of claim 1, wherein one or more of the plurality of objects are associated with one or more posts on a third-party website, respectively.
7. The method of claim 6, wherein, for each object associated with a post on a third-party website, the comments associated with the object are implemented using a social plug-in associated with the online social network.
8. The method of claim 1, wherein classifying the one or more test objects as associated with the first object-classification comprises scoring each test object by comparing the comments associated with the test object to the first set of features.
9. The method of claim 8, wherein scoring each test object further comprises scoring each comment associated with the test object.
10. The method of claim 9, wherein scoring each test object further comprises calculating a test object score by combining the scores of each comment associated with the test object.
11. The method of claim 9, wherein scoring each test object further comprises calculating a test object score by averaging the scores of each comment associated with the test object.
12. The method of claim 1, wherein the feature score of each feature is based at least in part on a frequency of occurrence of the feature in comments associated with one or more objects associated with the first object-classification.
13. The method of claim 1, wherein classifying the one or more test objects as associated with the first object-classification comprises comparing each test object to a set of filtering criteria.
14. The method of claim 13, wherein the set of filtering criteria is based on metadata associated with the test objects and comments associated with the test objects.
15. The method of claim 14, wherein the metadata comprises one or more of:
a number of associated comments;
inclusion or exclusion of one or more text strings;
inclusion or exclusion of one or more punctuation marks;
an association with one or more object-types;
an association with one or more languages;
an association with one or more places, entities, or resource-types;
an association with one or more other objects; or
an association with a particular period of time.
16. The method of claim 15, wherein the one or more punctuation marks comprise one or more of a question mark or exclamation mark.
17. The method of claim 15, wherein the one or more object-types comprise one or more of photos, posts, pages, applications, events, locations, or user groups.
18. The method of claim 1, wherein generating the final-object classifier algorithm further comprises one or more iterations of a training process, each iteration comprising:
accessing, from the plurality of objects, a randomly selected set of test objects;
classifying, by the final object-classifier algorithm, one or more test objects of the randomly selected set of test objects as associated with the first object-classification;
identifying, by the final object-classifier algorithm, from comments associated with the one or more classified test objects of the randomly selected set of test objects, a third set of features having feature scores greater than a threshold feature score; and
adding, to the final object-classifier algorithm, the third set of features to generate a revised final object-classifier algorithm.
